|Gare Saint-Charles- "Marseille Colonie Grecque" and  "Marseille Porte d'Orient" 
|[[Marseille]]
|align="center"|1911 to 1925
|This principal railway station has a large flight of stairs designed by the architects Eugène Sénès and Léon Arnal and using reinforced concrete. The competition for the designs of the stairway, intended to improve movement between the town centre and the railway station forecourt, was opened in 1911but the 1914-1918 war delayed completion of the project until 1925.  The stairs run from the railway station to the Boulevard d'Athènes.  The area is the site of much sculptural work including a group of lions and children by Arry Bitter<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ary.bitter.free.fr/accueil/cad_monumental.html
|title=Arry Bitter|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref> and the works  "Marseille Colonie Grecque" and  "Marseille Porte d'Orient" by Carli.  There are also six small bronze groups representing the produce of [[Provence]].  These are by Henri Raybaud and cover "les vendages", "les fruits", "la pêche", "les fleurs", "la moisson" and  "la chasse".  At bottom of either side of the main stairs are two large sculptures by [[Louis Botinelly]], one, called "Colonies d'Asie" represents colonial Asia and the other, called "Colonies d'Afrique", represents colonial Africa.<ref>Richard Dreiss, ''The Cathedral of the Winged Wheel and the Sugarbeet Station'', BoD – Books on Demand, 2013, p. 59 [https://books.google.com/books?id=KQ1Dtm4b5w4C&pg=PA59&dq=%22Louis+Botinelly%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=16SaUueiG8XN7AbLjYCQDg&ved=0CEUQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=%22Louis%20Botinelly%22&f=false]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/mersri_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=IA13000800
|title=Gare Saint-Charles|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref>
[[File:Escalier de la gare Saint Charles Marseille, Carli.JPG|thumb|centre|250px|"Marseille Porte de l'Orient' by Auguste Carli along the main staircase of the Gare Saint-Charles]]
